01:04:46.116 --> 01:04:48.726
That will affect the
quality of the grapes.

01:04:48.726 --> 01:04:53.726
And so presumably the wine
industry might move north.

01:04:54.684 --> 01:04:56.900
Though, of course, there
a lot of scientists

01:04:56.900 --> 01:04:59.160
who are experimenting and
trying to create grapes

01:04:59.160 --> 01:05:03.010
that will be able to still do well

01:05:03.010 --> 01:05:04.890
even if the climate is hotter.

01:05:04.890 --> 01:05:09.890
But I think the drought has
had an affect on California.

01:05:10.183 --> 01:05:13.880
Certainly last year, the
yields were much lower

01:05:13.880 --> 01:05:16.770
because the plants were more stressed out.

01:05:16.770 --> 01:05:18.620
And I think they're probably
gonna do okay this year.

01:05:18.620 --> 01:05:21.820
But definitely climate
change is a very major worry

01:05:21.820 --> 01:05:25.363
for grape growers and wine makers.

01:05:28.480 --> 01:05:29.620
- [Audience Member] I
wanted to ask if you could

01:05:29.620 --> 01:05:31.450
share some of the history about

01:05:34.012 --> 01:05:36.121
University of California at Berkeley being

01:05:36.121 --> 01:05:39.964
the university farm and
later one Davis becoming our

01:05:39.964 --> 01:05:41.847
university farm.

01:05:41.847 --> 01:05:46.493
Just how viticulture came to be a part of

01:05:46.493 --> 01:05:50.661
the body of knowledge of the
University of California.

01:05:50.661 --> 01:05:52.250
- So the question is sort of

01:05:52.250 --> 01:05:57.170
how did viticulture evolve in the halls

01:05:57.170 --> 01:05:58.637
of academia in California.

01:05:58.637 --> 01:06:01.841
So of course the original
and only university,

01:06:01.841 --> 01:06:05.620
public university, in
California was here at Berkeley

01:06:05.620 --> 01:06:06.669
for a very long time.

01:06:06.669 --> 01:06:08.750
And we--
- And Isaias Hellman

01:06:08.750 --> 01:06:10.400
was a regent for--
- Yes, he was a regent

01:06:10.400 --> 01:06:11.233
for--
- A long period.

01:06:11.233 --> 01:06:13.398
- 38 years he was a regent, I believe.

01:06:13.398 --> 01:06:17.810
So there was a man, I think
his name was Mr. Bioletti

01:06:17.810 --> 01:06:19.800
who headed up a very important

01:06:21.270 --> 01:06:24.752
department at UC Berkeley
that studied wine.

01:06:24.752 --> 01:06:27.950
And that, in itself, is a
very interesting history,

01:06:27.950 --> 01:06:31.637
because he brought an academic
perspective to making wine.

01:06:31.637 --> 01:06:34.720
And he had his supporters.

01:06:34.720 --> 01:06:36.340
But there were a lot of businessmen

01:06:36.340 --> 01:06:38.900
who fought, like his approach towards wine

01:06:38.900 --> 01:06:41.200
was ridiculous and unnecessary.

01:06:41.200 --> 01:06:43.872
And those supporters eventually convinced

01:06:43.872 --> 01:06:47.612
the legislature to unfund
him in a lot of ways.

01:06:47.612 --> 01:06:52.349
And so once Davis was founded,

01:06:52.349 --> 01:06:53.913
the whole wine-making,

01:06:53.913 --> 01:06:57.520
the study of wine and stuff
was moved up to UC Davis.

01:06:57.520 --> 01:07:00.824
So really from the very start,

01:07:00.824 --> 01:07:03.090
Berkeley has been very involved

01:07:03.090 --> 01:07:04.890
in trying to create better grapes,

01:07:04.890 --> 01:07:07.730
studying the conditions under
which grapes flourished,

01:07:07.730 --> 01:07:11.380
sort of measuring the
temperatures of different areas

01:07:11.380 --> 01:07:13.540
in California to determine climates

01:07:13.540 --> 01:07:14.773
and all sorts of things.

01:07:14.773 --> 01:07:16.610
So it's been very, very critical

01:07:16.610 --> 01:07:18.770
but politics have also played a role

01:07:18.770 --> 01:07:21.743
in how those kind of
departments have done.

01:07:23.289 --> 01:07:24.480
- [Audience Member] I seem to remember

01:07:24.480 --> 01:07:26.390
that there's a connection
with the Hellman name

01:07:26.390 --> 01:07:28.870
to the Ehrman Mansion in West Lake Tahoe.

01:07:28.870 --> 01:07:31.070
Is it the same Hellman family?

01:07:31.070 --> 01:07:33.450
- Yes, so the question
is there's a connection

01:07:33.450 --> 01:07:36.530
between the Hellmans and
the Ehrmans in Tahoe.

01:07:36.530 --> 01:07:40.090
So Isaias Hellman, who I
write about in Towers of Gold,

01:07:40.090 --> 01:07:43.090
he built a beautiful
house on the western shore

01:07:43.090 --> 01:07:45.340
of California, of Lake Tahoe,

01:07:45.340 --> 01:07:47.350
called Sugar Pine Point, he named it.

01:07:47.350 --> 01:07:51.360
And after he died, his
daughter inherited it.

01:07:51.360 --> 01:07:53.690
And her name was Florence Hellman-Ehrman.

01:07:53.690 --> 01:07:55.730
She was married to Sidney Ehrman.

01:07:55.730 --> 01:07:59.200
So the place has something
called the Ehrman Mansion on it.

01:07:59.200 --> 01:08:00.140
So that's the answer.

01:08:00.140 --> 01:08:02.260
- [Deirdre] It's a state park now?

01:08:02.260 --> 01:08:03.198
- It's a state park, yes.

01:08:03.198 --> 01:08:06.948
So, yeah, it was taken by
eminent domain by California

01:08:06.948 --> 01:08:09.540
in 1968 and people were
very upset about it.

01:08:09.540 --> 01:08:11.940
But I think in retrospect
it was a good thing,

01:08:11.940 --> 01:08:14.700
because now there's two
miles of open shoreline

01:08:14.700 --> 01:08:16.020
for everyone to enjoy.

01:08:16.020 --> 01:08:17.890
- [Deirdre] Yeah, great.

01:08:17.890 --> 01:08:19.800
- [Audience Member] You've described

01:08:19.800 --> 01:08:22.981
the cross-section of the
Jewish history of California.

01:08:22.981 --> 01:08:25.120
Is that really the California history?

01:08:25.120 --> 01:08:27.690
It seems like such a large part of it,

01:08:27.690 --> 01:08:30.036
and yet Jews were such a small
part of the population here.

01:08:30.036 --> 01:08:33.850
So I'm wondering whether
we're simply seeing

01:08:33.850 --> 01:08:36.720
a focus on that from your discussion.

01:08:36.720 --> 01:08:38.230
Obviously, you've researched it.

01:08:38.230 --> 01:08:40.222
Or whether it was as big as it sounds.

01:08:40.222 --> 01:08:42.415
And if it was as big as it sounds,

01:08:42.415 --> 01:08:44.630
how did it get so big?

01:08:44.630 --> 01:08:45.598
- That's a very good question.

01:08:45.598 --> 01:08:46.890
Yeah, I don't know
(Deirdre chuckles)

01:08:46.890 --> 01:08:47.960
how to answer that.

01:08:47.960 --> 01:08:50.720
Maybe, yeah, Jews are
a very small percentage

01:08:50.720 --> 01:08:52.603
of the population in California.

01:08:53.730 --> 01:08:56.530
But perhaps they had an outside influence

01:08:56.530 --> 01:08:58.450
certainly in the early days of California,

01:08:58.450 --> 01:09:01.970
just because of the tremendous
financial success they had

01:09:01.970 --> 01:09:03.500
and how they spent their money

01:09:03.500 --> 01:09:05.603
and their philanthropic endeavors.

01:09:08.740 --> 01:09:10.270
I mean, we could be talking about

01:09:10.270 --> 01:09:11.700
Irish history up here, too,

01:09:11.700 --> 01:09:14.050
and there would be a lot
to say about Irish history

01:09:14.050 --> 01:09:15.171
or Chinese history.

01:09:15.171 --> 01:09:18.177
It's just that I happened
to have written about it,

01:09:18.177 --> 01:09:22.000
that's why it's the focus
of this conversation.

01:09:22.000 --> 01:09:24.150
- [Audience Member]
And a related question.

01:09:25.680 --> 01:09:29.770
One block in San Francisco,
with multiple residents

01:09:29.770 --> 01:09:33.380
from Reckendorf, Germany, all born

01:09:33.380 --> 01:09:34.550
at the same period of time,

01:09:34.550 --> 01:09:37.120
all raised in the same town of 900,

01:09:37.120 --> 01:09:38.660
all find their way here eventually,

01:09:38.660 --> 01:09:42.831
all are monumental names in
the history of California.

01:09:42.831 --> 01:09:44.781
They're wonderfully successful.

01:09:44.781 --> 01:09:46.730
They have families that were

01:09:46.730 --> 01:09:48.655
wonderfully successful for generations.

01:09:48.655 --> 01:09:52.281
But the starting point is this
little spot in Reckendorf.

01:09:52.281 --> 01:09:55.312
What in the water there--

01:09:55.312 --> 01:09:57.274
(audience and speakers laughing)

01:09:57.274 --> 01:10:00.680
I'm wondering whether
it's just the fact that

01:10:00.680 --> 01:10:05.550
Europeans in 1850 knew what
the future of the United States

01:10:05.550 --> 01:10:07.700
in 1851 was gonna look like

01:10:07.700 --> 01:10:10.069
because we were still living in 1820.

01:10:10.069 --> 01:10:11.100
- Yes.

01:10:11.100 --> 01:10:13.566
- I didn't get the last part.

01:10:13.566 --> 01:10:15.380
- [Audience Member]
Well, the United States

01:10:15.380 --> 01:10:17.660
was behind Europe in terms of its cultural

01:10:17.660 --> 01:10:19.650
and economic and political and

01:10:19.650 --> 01:10:21.260
artistic development.
- You know, I think

01:10:21.260 --> 01:10:23.460
this touches, if I may
throw something in here,

01:10:23.460 --> 01:10:26.200
on the advantages of being
discriminated against

01:10:26.200 --> 01:10:27.535
in some situations,

01:10:27.535 --> 01:10:31.440
that when Frances discussed the fact that

01:10:31.440 --> 01:10:35.147
Jews could not own property
in Germany, were not citizens.

01:10:35.147 --> 01:10:39.607
And in other central and eastern
European countries as well.

01:10:39.607 --> 01:10:41.814
So they were motivated to emigrate,

01:10:41.814 --> 01:10:46.300
whereas other young men who
would have good prospects

01:10:46.300 --> 01:10:48.953
in Europe perhaps wouldn't
have been as motivated.

01:10:48.953 --> 01:10:51.960
After all, it's mainly
the poor who emigrate.

01:10:51.960 --> 01:10:52.910
- [Deirdre] Right.

01:10:52.910 --> 01:10:54.516
- But in this case it was

01:10:54.516 --> 01:10:59.516
well educated middle-class Jews who--

01:11:00.137 --> 01:11:02.080
- [Audience Member]
Except Isais was what, 16.

01:11:02.080 --> 01:11:03.470
How well educated can he be?

01:11:03.470 --> 01:11:04.380
Or was he?

01:11:04.380 --> 01:11:06.100
Was he high school European educated?

01:11:06.100 --> 01:11:06.933
- Yeah.

01:11:06.933 --> 01:11:08.910
- I mean, they weren't exactly middle cla,

01:11:08.910 --> 01:11:13.123
I mean, they had the money to
send their children overseas.

01:11:14.550 --> 01:11:17.213
Yeah, but actually the middle-class Jews,

01:11:17.213 --> 01:11:20.170
when restrictions were
loosened in Germany,

01:11:20.170 --> 01:11:22.891
starting in 1860s, many of
them went to the cities.

01:11:22.891 --> 01:11:25.253
And they didn't come to America.

01:11:26.350 --> 01:11:28.160
But the question about
the water in Reckendorf

01:11:28.160 --> 01:11:28.993
is a really good one.

01:11:28.993 --> 01:11:31.031
I did find out in my research that

01:11:31.031 --> 01:11:34.890
at least eight men who
came from Reckendorf

01:11:34.890 --> 01:11:37.896
became multi-millionaires
in the 19th Century.

01:11:37.896 --> 01:11:40.050
- [Deirdre] Did they all
go to the same school?

01:11:40.050 --> 01:11:42.435
- They probably all went to
the same little Jewish school.

01:11:42.435 --> 01:11:45.635
(chuckles) That teacher might've
been the glue, who knows?

01:11:45.635 --> 01:11:46.973
(audience laughing)

01:11:46.973 --> 01:11:48.170
- Yeah, that would be interesting.

01:11:48.170 --> 01:11:49.612
- [Audience Member] Eight
Jews from Reckendorf.

01:11:49.612 --> 01:11:50.445
- Right.

01:11:50.445 --> 01:11:51.445
- Eight.
- Probably went

01:11:51.445 --> 01:11:52.739
to the same synagogue, too.

01:11:52.739 --> 01:11:53.572
- The same synagogue.
- Yes, there's only

01:11:53.572 --> 01:11:54.405
one synagogue.
- I mean, there's probably

01:11:54.405 --> 01:11:56.540
somewhere back there,
there's probably some figure

01:11:56.540 --> 01:11:57.970
that would be interesting to discover.

01:11:57.970 --> 01:12:00.350
You know, one might guess that
there would be some educator

01:12:00.350 --> 01:12:05.020
or rabbi who played a role
in their formative times.

01:12:05.020 --> 01:12:08.040
I just would comment one thing about your

01:12:08.040 --> 01:12:09.960
saying how do you get into proportion,

01:12:09.960 --> 01:12:12.009
how much is the Jewish
history of California

01:12:12.009 --> 01:12:13.825
the history of California,

01:12:13.825 --> 01:12:15.717
or how much did Jews create California,

01:12:15.717 --> 01:12:19.410
that I don't think we can give
a definitive answer to that.

01:12:19.410 --> 01:12:21.500
But what I would add to this is that

01:12:21.500 --> 01:12:23.950
I think the story of the Jewish role

01:12:23.950 --> 01:12:26.110
in the creation of California

01:12:26.110 --> 01:12:29.080
actually was a little-known story.

01:12:29.080 --> 01:12:32.910
And so I think Frances',
one of the importance

01:12:32.910 --> 01:12:36.430
of Frances' work, has been
in surfacing that story.

01:12:36.430 --> 01:12:38.940
And then perhaps it's for
other people to try to

01:12:38.940 --> 01:12:41.140
get it into proportion,

01:12:41.140 --> 01:12:45.460
or say the importance of that
story relative to others.

01:12:45.460 --> 01:12:49.070
But it's a story that
really had not been told.

01:12:49.070 --> 01:12:50.910
There's a wonderful documentary movie.

01:12:50.910 --> 01:12:53.791
And I know you played a
role and you're in it,

01:12:53.791 --> 01:12:57.260
by a woman named Jackie Krentzman

01:12:57.260 --> 01:13:00.480
that's called American Jerusalem.

01:13:00.480 --> 01:13:03.560
And American Jerusalem is San Francisco.

01:13:03.560 --> 01:13:06.880
And it is another attempt,
and a very recent one,

01:13:06.880 --> 01:13:08.152
just within the past two years,

01:13:08.152 --> 01:13:10.052
a few years, but it was on PBS,

01:13:10.052 --> 01:13:13.549
to tell that untold story

01:13:13.549 --> 01:13:18.480
that the Jews of San Francisco

01:13:18.480 --> 01:13:20.430
did play an important role,

01:13:20.430 --> 01:13:22.020
maybe not the all-important role,

01:13:22.020 --> 01:13:24.670
but an important role in the development

01:13:24.670 --> 01:13:26.700
of the economy and the culture

01:13:26.700 --> 01:13:28.600
that we are still living in today.

01:13:28.600 --> 01:13:32.170
It's very, very much the
heirs of the institutions

01:13:32.170 --> 01:13:33.223
that they created.

01:13:34.520 --> 01:13:35.737
So, yes?

01:13:35.737 --> 01:13:37.780
- [Audience Member] Hi, thank you.

01:13:37.780 --> 01:13:39.186
Just moving up to the modern day.

01:13:39.186 --> 01:13:40.884
I wanted to ask you, Frances,

01:13:40.884 --> 01:13:45.320
about given the focus on
the HarvEst lecture series

01:13:45.320 --> 01:13:47.010
and its focus on women,

01:13:47.010 --> 01:13:49.776
if you might speak to your own experience

01:13:49.776 --> 01:13:51.940
as a prominent woman author

01:13:51.940 --> 01:13:53.690
and as co-founder of Berkeleyside,

01:13:53.690 --> 01:13:55.350
and then also perhaps to touch on,

01:13:55.350 --> 01:13:56.770
because I'm curious about it,

01:13:56.770 --> 01:13:58.334
women in the wine industry today.

01:13:58.334 --> 01:14:02.150
- Yes, so I do.

01:14:02.150 --> 01:14:05.210
One of my main characters
in my book is a woman.

01:14:05.210 --> 01:14:06.615
Her name is Delia Viader.

01:14:06.615 --> 01:14:09.650
She had grown up in Argentina.

01:14:09.650 --> 01:14:14.650
Her family had Spanish
roots and French roots.

01:14:14.868 --> 01:14:18.940
She is one of the first really prominent

01:14:18.940 --> 01:14:21.855
female wine makers in Napa.

01:14:21.855 --> 01:14:26.630
She lost about four-and-a-half
million dollars worth of wine

01:14:26.630 --> 01:14:28.908
in that fire, she was uninsured.

01:14:28.908 --> 01:14:31.160
This woman has an incredible spirit

01:14:31.160 --> 01:14:32.637
and an incredible drive.

01:14:32.637 --> 01:14:34.440
And she was able to recover

01:14:34.440 --> 01:14:36.621
from that devastating financial loss.

01:14:36.621 --> 01:14:41.621
And so there are a number of
female wine makers in Napa.

01:14:42.980 --> 01:14:44.394
I mean, it's been a place where

01:14:44.394 --> 01:14:47.313
women have thrived as much as men.

01:14:47.313 --> 01:14:50.213
And there are a lot of iconic names.

01:14:51.670 --> 01:14:53.380
So, anyway.

01:14:53.380 --> 01:14:55.151
- You know, I'm glad that
you mentioned Berkeleyside,

01:14:55.151 --> 01:14:56.880
because we didn't get to that.

01:14:56.880 --> 01:14:58.570
But Frances is one of the founders

01:14:58.570 --> 01:15:00.350
and she's a reporter and editor

01:15:00.350 --> 01:15:05.350
for Berkeleyside, an online
local, hyper-local newspaper,

01:15:06.459 --> 01:15:09.760
or news site that I think we can all

01:15:09.760 --> 01:15:11.770
be very grateful for.

01:15:11.770 --> 01:15:13.669
And it plays a really important role.

01:15:13.669 --> 01:15:15.939
And I hope if any of you have not,

01:15:15.939 --> 01:15:20.008
don't look at it, you'll
Google it and go look at it.

01:15:20.008 --> 01:15:23.674
So, thank you very much.
- Thank you.

